GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
H 1
HOUSE BILL 657
Short Title: Duke's Rescue Act. (Public)
Sponsors: Representatives Ross, Carney, Cotham, and Ward (Primary Sponsors).
For a complete list of sponsors, refer to the North Carolina General Assembly web site.
Referred to: Wildlife Resources, if favorable, Judiciary 2, if favorable, Rules, Calendar, and
Operations of the House
April 2, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO PROVIDE MINIMAL STANDARDS OF CARE FOR COMPANION ANIMALS.
3 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
4 SECTION 1. Article 47 of Chapter 14 of the General Statutes is amended by adding
5 a new section to read:
6 "§ 14-360.5. Care of companion animals.
7 (a) Minimum Standards. – Except as set forth in subsection (b) of this section, any person
8 who owns a companion animal shall provide all of the following:
9 (1) Adequate care.
10 (2) Adequate exercise.
11 (3) Adequate feed.
12 (4) Adequate shelter.
13 (5) Adequate space.
14 (6) Adequate water.
15 (7) Appropriate veterinary treatment, including emergency veterinary treatment.
16 (b) Exception. – The requirements of this section pertaining to adequate shelter and
17 adequate space shall not apply to any of the following:
18 (1) The use of a dog in a lawful hunt.
19 (2) The use of a restraint on a dog while the owner and dog engage in conduct
20 directly related to the business of shepherding or herding cattle or livestock.
21 (3) The use of a restraint on a dog while the owner and dog engage in conduct
22 directly related to the business of cultivating agricultural products.
23 (4) The use of a restraint on a dog pursuant to the requirements of a camping or
24 recreational area.
25 (c) Definitions. – The following definitions apply in this section:
26 (1) Adequate care. – The responsible practice of good animal husbandry,
27 handling, confinement, feeding, watering, protection, shelter, transportation,
28 treatment, and, when necessary, euthanasia, appropriate for the age, species,
29 condition, size, and type of the animal and the provision of veterinary care
30 when needed to prevent suffering or impairment of health.
31 (2) Adequate exercise. – The opportunity for the animal to move sufficiently to
32 maintain normal muscle tone and mass for the age, species, size, and condition
33 of the animal.
*H657-v-1*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (3) Adequate feed. – The provision of food meeting all of the following
2 requirements:
3 a. It is of sufficient quantity and nutritive value to maintain the animal in
4 good health.
5 b. It is accessible to the animal.
6 c. It is prepared so as to permit ease of consumption for the animal's age,
7 species, condition, size, and type.
8 d. It is provided in a clean and sanitary manner to minimize
9 contamination by excrement and pests.
10 e. It is provided at suitable intervals for the species, age, and condition
11 of the animal, but at least once daily, except as otherwise prescribed
12 by a veterinarian.
13 (4) Adequate shelter. – Shelter that meets all of the conditions of this subdivision.
14 Adequate shelter does not include the outdoor tethering of an animal during
15 any period of extreme weather at the site where the animal is tethered.
16 a. The shelter is suitable for the species, age, condition, size, and type of
17 each animal.
18 b. The shelter protects each animal from injury, rain, sleet, snow, hail,
19 direct sunlight, the adverse effects of heat or cold, physical suffering,
20 and impairment of health.
21 c. The shelter is properly lighted and cleaned and enables each animal to
22 remain clean and dry, except when detrimental to the species. For
23 purposes of this subdivision, shelter is properly cleaned when (i)
24 carcasses, debris, food waste, and excrement are removed from the
25 primary enclosure with sufficient frequency to minimize the animals'
26 contact with those contaminants; (ii) the primary enclosure is sanitized
27 with sufficient frequency to minimize odors and the hazards of
28 disease; and (iii) the primary enclosure is cleaned so as to prevent the
29 animals confined therein from being directly or indirectly sprayed with
30 the stream of water or directly or indirectly exposed to hazardous
31 chemicals or disinfectants.
32 d. The shelter is properly shaded and does not readily conduct heat during
33 periods when the ambient air temperature at the shelter is greater than
34 85 degrees Fahrenheit.
35 e. The shelter provides a windbreak at its entrance and, during periods
36 when the ambient air temperature at the shelter is less than 32 degrees
37 Fahrenheit, bedding material consisting of straw, cedar shavings, or
38 the equivalent sufficient to protect the animal from cold and promote
39 the retention of body heat.
40 f. For dogs and cats, the shelter provides a solid surface, resting platform,
41 pad, floormat, or similar device that is large enough for the animal to
42 lie on in a normal manner and can be maintained in a sanitary manner.
43 g. The shelter's wire, grid, or slat floors (i) do not permit the animals' feet
44 to pass through the openings, (ii) do not sag under the animals' weight,
45 and (iii) protect the animals' feet and toes from injury.
46 (5) Adequate space. – Sufficient space to allow each animal to (i) easily stand, sit,
47 lie, turn about, and make all other normal body movements in a comfortable,
48 normal position for the animal and (ii) interact safely with other animals in the
49 enclosure. Adequate space for an animal that is tethered also includes all of
50 the following:
Page 2 House Bill 657-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 a. The tether to which the animal is attached permits freedom of
2 movement and is appropriate to the age and size of the animal; is
3 attached to the animal by a properly applied collar, halter, or harness
4 configured so as to protect the animal from injury and prevent the
5 animal or tether from becoming entangled with other objects or
6 animals or from extending over an object or edge that could result in
7 the strangulation or injury of the animal.
8 b. The tether is at least 15 feet in length or four times the length of the
9 animal, as measured from the tip of its nose to the base of its tail,
10 whichever is greater, except when the animal is being walked on a
11 leash or is attached by a tether to a lead line; does not, by its material,
12 size, or weight or any other characteristic, cause injury or pain to the
13 animal.
14 c. The tether does not weigh more than one-tenth of the animal's body
15 weight and does not have weights or other heavy objects attached to
16 it.
17 d. Tethering does not include the walking of an animal on a leash.
18 (6) Adequate water. – The provision of access to clean, fresh, potable water of a
19 drinkable temperature that meets the following requirements:
20 a. The water is provided in a suitable manner, in sufficient volume, and
21 at suitable intervals appropriate for the weather and temperature to
22 maintain normal hydration for the age, species, condition, size, and
23 type of each animal, except as prescribed by a veterinarian or as
24 dictated by naturally occurring states of hibernation or fasting normal
25 for the species.
26 b. The water is provided in clean, durable receptacles that are accessible
27 to each animal and are placed so as to minimize contamination of the
28 water by excrement and pests or an alternative source of hydration
29 consistent with generally accepted husbandry practices.
30 (7) Companion animal. – Any domestic dog or domestic cat. The term does not
31 include animals being raised for human consumption, whether for their meat,
32 milk, or eggs.
33 (8) Emergency veterinary treatment. – Veterinary treatment to stabilize a
34 life-threatening condition, alleviate suffering, prevent further disease
35 transmission, or prevent further disease progression.
36 (9) Extreme weather. – Any of the following:
37 a. The effective period of a hurricane warning or tropical storm warning
38 issued for the area by the National Weather Service.
39 b. The effective period for a heat advisory issued by a local or State
40 authority.
41 c. Any period when the actual or effective outdoor temperature is (i) at
42 or in excess of 85 degrees Fahrenheit or (ii) at or below 32 degrees
43 Fahrenheit.
44 d. The effective period for a severe weather warning issued for the area
45 by the National Weather Service, including a hurricane, tropical storm,
46 winter storm, tornado, or severe thunderstorm warning.
47 (10) Owner, or to own. – With respect to companion animals, includes any person
48 who (i) has a right of property in an animal, (ii) keeps or harbors an animal,
49 (iii) has an animal in his or her care, or (iv) acts as a custodian of an animal.
50 (11) Tethering. – To restrain a companion animal by tying the animal to any object
51 or structure, including a house, tree, fence, post, garage, or shed, by any
House Bill 657-First Edition Page 3

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 means, including, without limitation, a chain, rope, cord, leash, or running
2 line. Tethering shall not include the use of a leash to walk a companion animal.
3 (12) Veterinary treatment. – Treatment of a companion animal by or on the order
4 of a duly licensed veterinarian.
5 (d) Violation. – A violation of this section is punishable as follows:
6 (1) For a first offense under this section, the person is guilty of a Class 3
7 misdemeanor.
8 (2) For a second or subsequent offense under this section, the person is guilty of
9 a Class 2 misdemeanor."
10 SECTION 2. Any local ordinances regulating the standard of care for companion
11 animals that were adopted prior to the date this act becomes law may remain in effect after this
12 act becomes law. The governing body of a county or city may adopt ordinances regulating the
13 standard of care for companion animals after the date this act becomes law if the ordinances meet
14 or exceed the requirements of G.S. 14-360.5, as enacted in Section 1 of this act.
15 SECTION 3. This act becomes effective December 1, 2025, and applies to offenses
16 committed on or after that date.
